{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Research AlphaEvolve from Google DeepMind (2025). Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (available to you). Find primary sources: the DeepMind blog post, the white paper/PDF, and credible coverage.\n\nI need DETAILED, SPECIFIC, CITED facts about:\n1. The architecture: evolutionary coding pipeline using an ensemble of Gemini LLMs (Flash + Pro) that mutate/edit code, combined with AUTOMATED EVALUATORS that score each candidate program. Explain how the evolutionary loop works (population, mutation via LLM diffs, selection by evaluator score).\n2. The CRITICAL role of the verifier/evaluation function: AlphaEvolve only works on problems with a machine-gradable/automatically-verifiable objective function. Explain why this is a fundamental constraint and what classes of problems it excludes (e.g. things you can't auto-evaluate).\n3. Concrete results/achievements: the 4x4 complex matrix multiplication improvement over Strassen (48 vs 49 multiplications), the 0.7% recovery of Google datacenter compute (Borg), TPU circuit/arithmetic improvements, Gemini training kernel speedups, advances on open math problems (e.g. ~50 problems, kissing number in 11 dimensions). Give specific numbers with sources.\n4. What AlphaEvolve CANNOT do — stated limits: it does not improve its own LLMs/weights; it requires a verifier; not applicable to problems lacking automated evaluation. Quote DeepMind's own caveats.\n\nFor each fact provide the exact source URL. Prefer deepmind.google, arxiv, and the white paper. Return a structured list of falsifiable claims each with its URL."},"uuid":"1878e152-02b4-4222-a48c-2a9709d65e42","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:07.716Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
