{"parentUuid":"95b6367b-2bc6-4b11-9a20-bdc1a52c5bd0","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01SrVkBLXvpsa1dVrbn7fVtF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RBehCJCCisSrV9RUbXutVm","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Search AlphaEvolve limitations","prompt":"Use WebSearch and WebFetch to research the LIMITATIONS / WHAT ALPHAEVOLVE CANNOT DO for Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve (2025). I need specific, cited facts with exact source URLs and verbatim quotes.\n\nFocus on:\n- AlphaEvolve does NOT improve its own underlying LLMs / does not modify Gemini's weights (it is not recursive self-improvement of the model itself)\n- It REQUIRES an automated verifier/evaluator — it cannot be applied to problems lacking automated evaluation\n- The main limitation stated by DeepMind: it handles problems whose solutions can be \"described as algorithms\" and \"automatically evaluated\"; problems requiring manual experimentation are excluded\n- Any DeepMind caveats about scope, generality, future work\n- Any commentary on whether this is/isn't \"recursive self-improvement\" or AGI\n\nPrefer primary sources: deepmind.google blog post (\"AlphaEvolve a Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms\"), the arxiv/DeepMind white paper PDF (look at the Limitations and Conclusion sections). Also credible coverage (MIT Tech Review, Ars Technica, IEEE Spectrum) for how experts framed the limits.\n\nReturn a list of falsifiable, specific claims. Each claim MUST have its exact source URL. Quote DeepMind's own caveats VERBATIM where possible. Do not write files — return findings as your final text message.","subagent_type":"general-purpose"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9436,"cache_read_input_tokens":5811,"output_tokens":2888,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":9436},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2888,"cache_read_input_tokens":5811,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9436,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":9436,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":12318}}},"requestId":"req_011CcG22BJ37tz9rnNVRZGKY","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"2a8d5bab-5e03-4247-b4a8-6756acc07220","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:52.325Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"95b6367b-2bc6-4b11-9a20-bdc1a52c5bd0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AVQZqnCfzKZvFRNdGX38Q5","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have all four claims from both primary sources, cross-checked. Note one discrepancy worth flagging: the blog post says FlashAttention \"up to a 32.5% speedup\" while the white paper says \"sped up by 32%\". Both are primary DeepMind sources.\n\nHere are the findings — four falsifiable claims, each cross-checked against the two primary DeepMind sources (the blog post and the white paper PDF).\n\n---\n\n## Sources used (both primary, DeepMind)\n- **Blog**: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- **White paper PDF** (DeepMind-hosted): https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n  (I extracted the PDF text locally; section/page references below are from the actual PDF body, not a secondary summary.)\n\n---\n\n## Claim 1 — Borg / datacenter scheduling: 0.7%, in production >1 year ✅ VERIFIED\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"This solution, now in production for over a year, continuously recovers, on average, 0.7% of Google's worldwide compute resources.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.1 \"Improving data center scheduling\" (verbatim):** \"Post-deployment measurements across Google's fleet confirmed the simulator results, revealing that this heuristic function continuously recovers on average 0.7% of Google's fleet-wide compute resources, which would otherwise be stranded.\"\n\nSupporting detail (white paper): framed as a \"vector bin-packing problem with two variables\" (CPU + memory); the heuristic only re-ranks machines Borg already deemed feasible, so decisions are \"effectively correct by construction.\" Chosen over a deep-RL approach for \"interpretability, debuggability, predictability, and ease of deployment.\" The blog supplies the \"over a year in production\" figure; the white paper does not restate the duration but confirms full-fleet rollout.\n\n- Numbers: **0.7%** of Google's worldwide/fleet-wide compute; **>1 year** in production.\n\n## Claim 2 — TPU Verilog/RTL arithmetic circuit ✅ VERIFIED (qualitative; no % given)\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"AlphaEvolve proposed a Verilog rewrite that removed unnecessary bits in a key, highly optimized arithmetic circuit for matrix multiplication.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.3 \"Assisting in hardware circuit design\" (verbatim):** \"AlphaEvolve was challenged to optimize an already highly optimized Verilog implementation of a key TPU arithmetic circuit within the matrix multiplication unit. The optimization objectives were to reduce both area and power consumption... AlphaEvolve was able to find a simple code rewrite that removed unnecessary bits, a change validated by TPU designers for correctness.\"\n\n**Important caveats from the white paper (often dropped in secondary coverage):**\n- \"While this specific improvement was also **independently caught by downstream synthesis tools**\" — i.e., the rewrite was not exclusively AlphaEvolve's discovery.\n- \"**Integrated into an upcoming TPU**, this improvement represents Gemini's first direct contribution to TPU arithmetic circuits.\"\n\n- Numbers: **none quantified.** The objectives were area + power reduction, but no percentage is reported. Any claim attaching a specific % to the TPU circuit is unsupported by the primary sources.\n\n## Claim 3 — Gemini training kernel: 23% kernel speedup → 1% training-time reduction ✅ VERIFIED\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"By finding smarter ways to divide a large matrix multiplication operation into more manageable subproblems, it sped up this vital kernel in Gemini's architecture by 23%, leading to a 1% reduction in Gemini's training time.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.2 \"Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering\" (verbatim):** \"This automated approach enables AlphaEvolve to discover a heuristic that yields an average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic, and a corresponding 1% reduction in Gemini's overall training time.\"\n\nMechanism (white paper): optimizing the **tiling heuristic** for a matrix-multiplication **Pallas kernel** (JAX) used to train Gemini, evaluated on real TPU accelerators. Also reduced kernel optimization time \"from several months... to just days,\" and \"has been deployed in production.\"\n\n- Numbers: **23%** average kernel speedup; **1%** reduction in overall Gemini training time. Both sources agree exactly. (\"Pallas\" is named in the white paper, not the blog.)\n\n## Claim 4 — FlashAttention kernel: 32% (paper) / 32.5% (blog) ⚠️ MINOR DISCREPANCY\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"AlphaEvolve achieved up to a **32.5%** speedup for the FlashAttention kernel implementation in Transformer-based AI models.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.4 \"Directly optimizing compiler-generated code\" (verbatim):** \"Firstly, the FlashAttention kernel for the configuration of interest was **sped up by 32%**. Secondly, AlphaEvolve found improvements in pre- and postprocessing of kernel inputs and outputs, resulting in a **15% speed up** in this part.\"\n\nMechanism (white paper): directly editing the **XLA-generated IR** wrapping the FlashAttention Pallas kernel; the optimized configuration was \"a highly impactful transformer model used for inference at scale on **GPUs**.\"\n\n- Numbers: **32% kernel speedup** (white paper) vs **\"up to 32.5%\"** (blog) — flag this; the blog is rounded/phrased as an upper bound, the paper states a flat 32%. Plus a separate **15%** speedup on pre/post-processing (white paper only; the blog omits the 15% figure).\n\n---\n\n## Summary table of falsifiable numbers\n\n| # | Claim | Number | Best source |\n|---|-------|--------|-------------|\n| 1 | Borg/datacenter compute recovered | **0.7%** of fleet-wide compute, **>1 yr** in production | Blog + paper §3.3.1 |\n| 2 | TPU Verilog matmul circuit | removed \"unnecessary bits\"; **no % given**; in an *upcoming* TPU; also caught by synthesis tools | Blog + paper §3.3.3 |\n| 3a | Gemini matmul/Pallas kernel speedup | **23%** (avg, vs expert heuristic) | Blog + paper §3.3.2 |\n| 3b | Gemini overall training-time reduction | **1%** | Blog + paper §3.3.2 |\n| 4a | FlashAttention kernel speedup | **32%** (paper) / **\"up to 32.5%\"** (blog) | Paper §3.3.4 / Blog |\n| 4b | FlashAttention pre/post-processing speedup | **15%** | Paper §3.3.4 only |\n\nThe only cross-source inconsistency is the FlashAttention figure (32% vs 32.5%). Everything else matches verbatim between the two primary DeepMind sources."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a51a7a37c07b9faa2 (use SendMessage with to: 'a51a7a37c07b9faa2' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 27835\ntool_uses: 10\nduration_ms: 94535</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"b5e9e154-fe53-44ea-a911-867ca6997686","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:21.238Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Use WebSearch and WebFetch to research the CONCRETE RESULTS on GOOGLE INFRASTRUCTURE / HARDWARE achieved by Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve (2025). I need specific numbers with exact source URLs.\n\nFocus on these specific claims and verify exact figures:\n- Recovering 0.7% of Google's worldwide datacenter compute resources via a scheduling heuristic for Borg (Google's cluster management system), and that it has been in production for over a year\n- TPU circuit / arithmetic design improvements (e.g. removing/simplifying unnecessary bits in a Verilog/RTL arithmetic circuit, proposed for an upcoming TPU)\n- Gemini training kernel speedups (e.g. optimizing matrix multiplication / tiling heuristics in Pallas kernels, ~23% kernel speedup leading to ~1% reduction in Gemini's overall training time)\n- FlashAttention kernel optimization in the compiler (e.g. up to 32% speedup of the FlashAttention kernel implementation)\n\nPrefer primary sources: deepmind.google blog post (\"AlphaEvolve a Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms\"), the arxiv/DeepMind white paper PDF. Cross-check numbers.\n\nReturn a list of falsifiable, specific claims with exact numbers. Each claim MUST have its exact source URL. Quote DeepMind's wording where possible. Do not write files — return findings as your final text message.","agentId":"a51a7a37c07b9faa2","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have all four claims from both primary sources, cross-checked. Note one discrepancy worth flagging: the blog post says FlashAttention \"up to a 32.5% speedup\" while the white paper says \"sped up by 32%\". Both are primary DeepMind sources.\n\nHere are the findings — four falsifiable claims, each cross-checked against the two primary DeepMind sources (the blog post and the white paper PDF).\n\n---\n\n## Sources used (both primary, DeepMind)\n- **Blog**: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- **White paper PDF** (DeepMind-hosted): https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n  (I extracted the PDF text locally; section/page references below are from the actual PDF body, not a secondary summary.)\n\n---\n\n## Claim 1 — Borg / datacenter scheduling: 0.7%, in production >1 year ✅ VERIFIED\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"This solution, now in production for over a year, continuously recovers, on average, 0.7% of Google's worldwide compute resources.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.1 \"Improving data center scheduling\" (verbatim):** \"Post-deployment measurements across Google's fleet confirmed the simulator results, revealing that this heuristic function continuously recovers on average 0.7% of Google's fleet-wide compute resources, which would otherwise be stranded.\"\n\nSupporting detail (white paper): framed as a \"vector bin-packing problem with two variables\" (CPU + memory); the heuristic only re-ranks machines Borg already deemed feasible, so decisions are \"effectively correct by construction.\" Chosen over a deep-RL approach for \"interpretability, debuggability, predictability, and ease of deployment.\" The blog supplies the \"over a year in production\" figure; the white paper does not restate the duration but confirms full-fleet rollout.\n\n- Numbers: **0.7%** of Google's worldwide/fleet-wide compute; **>1 year** in production.\n\n## Claim 2 — TPU Verilog/RTL arithmetic circuit ✅ VERIFIED (qualitative; no % given)\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"AlphaEvolve proposed a Verilog rewrite that removed unnecessary bits in a key, highly optimized arithmetic circuit for matrix multiplication.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.3 \"Assisting in hardware circuit design\" (verbatim):** \"AlphaEvolve was challenged to optimize an already highly optimized Verilog implementation of a key TPU arithmetic circuit within the matrix multiplication unit. The optimization objectives were to reduce both area and power consumption... AlphaEvolve was able to find a simple code rewrite that removed unnecessary bits, a change validated by TPU designers for correctness.\"\n\n**Important caveats from the white paper (often dropped in secondary coverage):**\n- \"While this specific improvement was also **independently caught by downstream synthesis tools**\" — i.e., the rewrite was not exclusively AlphaEvolve's discovery.\n- \"**Integrated into an upcoming TPU**, this improvement represents Gemini's first direct contribution to TPU arithmetic circuits.\"\n\n- Numbers: **none quantified.** The objectives were area + power reduction, but no percentage is reported. Any claim attaching a specific % to the TPU circuit is unsupported by the primary sources.\n\n## Claim 3 — Gemini training kernel: 23% kernel speedup → 1% training-time reduction ✅ VERIFIED\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"By finding smarter ways to divide a large matrix multiplication operation into more manageable subproblems, it sped up this vital kernel in Gemini's architecture by 23%, leading to a 1% reduction in Gemini's training time.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.2 \"Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering\" (verbatim):** \"This automated approach enables AlphaEvolve to discover a heuristic that yields an average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic, and a corresponding 1% reduction in Gemini's overall training time.\"\n\nMechanism (white paper): optimizing the **tiling heuristic** for a matrix-multiplication **Pallas kernel** (JAX) used to train Gemini, evaluated on real TPU accelerators. Also reduced kernel optimization time \"from several months... to just days,\" and \"has been deployed in production.\"\n\n- Numbers: **23%** average kernel speedup; **1%** reduction in overall Gemini training time. Both sources agree exactly. (\"Pallas\" is named in the white paper, not the blog.)\n\n## Claim 4 — FlashAttention kernel: 32% (paper) / 32.5% (blog) ⚠️ MINOR DISCREPANCY\n\n**Blog (verbatim):** \"AlphaEvolve achieved up to a **32.5%** speedup for the FlashAttention kernel implementation in Transformer-based AI models.\"\n\n**White paper §3.3.4 \"Directly optimizing compiler-generated code\" (verbatim):** \"Firstly, the FlashAttention kernel for the configuration of interest was **sped up by 32%**. Secondly, AlphaEvolve found improvements in pre- and postprocessing of kernel inputs and outputs, resulting in a **15% speed up** in this part.\"\n\nMechanism (white paper): directly editing the **XLA-generated IR** wrapping the FlashAttention Pallas kernel; the optimized configuration was \"a highly impactful transformer model used for inference at scale on **GPUs**.\"\n\n- Numbers: **32% kernel speedup** (white paper) vs **\"up to 32.5%\"** (blog) — flag this; the blog is rounded/phrased as an upper bound, the paper states a flat 32%. Plus a separate **15%** speedup on pre/post-processing (white paper only; the blog omits the 15% figure).\n\n---\n\n## Summary table of falsifiable numbers\n\n| # | Claim | Number | Best source |\n|---|-------|--------|-------------|\n| 1 | Borg/datacenter compute recovered | **0.7%** of fleet-wide compute, **>1 yr** in production | Blog + paper §3.3.1 |\n| 2 | TPU Verilog matmul circuit | removed \"unnecessary bits\"; **no % given**; in an *upcoming* TPU; also caught by synthesis tools | Blog + paper §3.3.3 |\n| 3a | Gemini matmul/Pallas kernel speedup | **23%** (avg, vs expert heuristic) | Blog + paper §3.3.2 |\n| 3b | Gemini overall training-time reduction | **1%** | Blog + paper §3.3.2 |\n| 4a | FlashAttention kernel speedup | **32%** (paper) / **\"up to 32.5%\"** (blog) | Paper §3.3.4 / Blog |\n| 4b | FlashAttention pre/post-processing speedup | **15%** | Paper §3.3.4 only |\n\nThe only cross-source inconsistency is the FlashAttention figure (32% vs 32.5%). Everything else matches verbatim between the two primary DeepMind sources."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":94535,"totalTokens":27835,"totalToolUseCount":10,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3384,"cache_read_input_tokens":21944,"output_tokens":2505,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3384},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2505,"cache_read_input_tokens":21944,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3384,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3384,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":5,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":5}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"95b6367b-2bc6-4b11-9a20-bdc1a52c5bd0","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"8fa77b85-f8e5-4d2a-b71e-6eb58af612dc","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01W15By2kkEbFpotSjuLLbFm","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive primary-source material from both the DeepMind blog and the white paper PDF. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Architecture: Cited, Falsifiable Claims\n\nTwo primary sources, both DeepMind:\n- **BLOG** = DeepMind blog post: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- **PAPER** = DeepMind white paper PDF (\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\", Novikov et al.): https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\n## The LLM ensemble (which models, and why two)\n\n1. **AlphaEvolve uses an ensemble of exactly two specific Gemini models.** PAPER §2.3, \"Models used\": *\"AlphaEvolve employs an ensemble of large language models. Specifically, we utilize a combination of Gemini 2.0 Flash and Gemini 2.0 Pro.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n2. **The ensemble exists to trade throughput against quality.** PAPER §2.3: *\"This ensemble approach allows us to balance computational throughput with the quality of generated solutions.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n3. **Flash is the breadth/throughput model.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Gemini 2.0 Flash, with its lower latency, enables a higher rate of candidate generation, increasing the number of ideas explored per unit of time.\"* The blog states it more compactly: Flash *\"maximizes the breadth of ideas explored.\"* (Sources: PAPER; BLOG)\n\n4. **Pro is the depth/quality model providing occasional breakthroughs.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Concurrently, Gemini 2.0 Pro, possessing greater capabilities, provides occasional, higher-quality suggestions that can significantly advance the evolutionary search and potentially lead to breakthroughs.\"* Blog: Gemini Pro *\"provides critical depth with insightful suggestions.\"* (Sources: PAPER; BLOG)\n\n5. **The stated optimization goal of the mix.** PAPER §2.3: *\"This strategic mix optimizes the overall discovery process by maximizing the volume of evaluated ideas while retaining the potential for substantial improvements driven by the more powerful model.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n6. **AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic and improves as the base LLM improves.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Although AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic, in ablations we observe that AlphaEvolve performs increasingly better as the underlying LLM improves.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## The evolutionary loop / pipeline components\n\n7. **The pipeline has four named components plus a controller loop.** PAPER (Figure 2 / §2 architecture) names them: **Prompt sampler**, **LLMs ensemble**, **Evaluators pool**, **Program database**, driven by a **Distributed Controller Loop**. (Source: PAPER)\n\n8. **The end-to-end loop, in DeepMind's words (PAPER §2 overview):** *\"AlphaEvolve then initiates an evolutionary loop. The Prompt sampler uses programs from the Program database to construct rich prompts (Section 2.2). Given these prompts, the LLMs generate code modifications (diffs), which are applied to create new programs (Section 2.3). These are then scored by Evaluators (Section 2.4), and promising solutions are registered back into the Program database (Section 2.5), driving the iterative [process].\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n9. **The core loop is captured as three lines of pseudocode.** PAPER (Distributed Controller Loop figure):\n   ```\n   diff = llm.generate(prompt)\n   child_program = apply_diff(parent_program, diff)\n   results = evaluator.execute(child_program)\n   ```\n   (Source: PAPER)\n\n10. **Blog-level restatement of the loop.** BLOG: *\"Together, these models propose computer programs that implement algorithmic solutions as code... AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics.\"* (Source: BLOG)\n\n11. **The prompt is assembled from prior solutions sampled from the database plus instructions.** PAPER §2.2: *\"This prompt comprises multiple previously discovered solutions sampled from the program database, as well as system instructions on how to propose changes to a particular solution.\"* It also supports explicit context, stochastic formatting, rendered evaluation results, and \"meta prompt evolution.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Code editing mechanism (diffs vs. full rewrites; codebase scope)\n\n12. **The default mutation mechanism is diff-based SEARCH/REPLACE blocks.** PAPER §2.3, \"Output format\": *\"When AlphaEvolve asks an LLM to modify existing code, especially within larger codebases, it requests the changes to be provided as a sequence of diff blocks in a specific format:\"* — the format being\n    ```\n    <<<<<<< SEARCH\n    # Original code block to be found and replaced\n    =======\n    # New code block to replace the original\n    >>>>>>> REPLACE\n    ```\n    *\"the code between <<<<<<< SEARCH and ======= is the exact segment to match in the current program version... This allows for targeted updates to specific parts of the code.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n13. **Full rewrites are an alternative configuration for short code.** PAPER §2.3: *\"In cases where the code being evolved is very short, or when a complete rewrite is more appropriate than a small modification, AlphaEvolve can be configured to instruct the LLM to output the entire code block directly, rather than using the diff format.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n14. **It edits within whole files/codebases, marking blocks to evolve with `EVOLVE-BLOCK` markers.** PAPER §2.1 / Figure 3: the user provides a file \"with blocks marked for evolution\" (`# EVOLVE-BLOCK-START` ... `# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END`) plus a special `evaluate` function; *\"it requests the changes... especially within larger codebases.\"* Levels of abstraction vary by problem — single functions up to bespoke search algorithms. (Source: PAPER)\n\n15. **It makes direct changes to code (not just single functions).** PAPER abstract: *\"AlphaEvolve orchestrates an autonomous pipeline of LLMs, whose task is to improve an algorithm by making direct changes to the code.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Evaluators / scoring\n\n16. **Candidates are scored by executing a user-provided evaluation function `h` returning scalar metrics.** PAPER §2.4: *\"each new solution proposed by the LLMs is automatically evaluated. In principle, this process amounts to simply executing the user-provided evaluation function h on the generated solution.\"* The function is \"a Python function, called evaluate, with a fixed input/output signature.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n17. **Evaluation supports a cascade (cheap-to-expensive filtering).** PAPER §2.4: *\"Evaluation cascade (hypothesis testing): the user can specify ensembles of test cases of increasing difficulty, such that new solutions are evaluated on the next stage only if they achieve sufficiently promising results in all earlier stages.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n18. **Optional LLM-generated feedback can add scores (e.g., for simplicity).** PAPER §2.4: properties \"difficult to capture precisely in the user-provided evaluation function... can be graded using separate LLM calls and added to the dictionary of scores to steer evolution.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n19. **AlphaEvolve supports multi-objective optimization, which it finds helps even a single target metric.** PAPER §2.4 \"Multiple scores\": *\"we find that even if one metric is of particular interest, optimizing for multiple metrics often improves results for the single target metric.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Program database / selection algorithm\n\n20. **The selection/storage algorithm is a combination of MAP-Elites and island-based population models.** PAPER §2.5: *\"In AlphaEvolve, the evolutionary database implements an algorithm that is inspired by a combination of the MAP elites algorithm [74] and island-based population models [83, 97].\"* Its goal: *\"balancing exploration and exploitation, to continuously improve the best programs while maintaining diversity.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n21. **The blog's plainer description of the database's role:** the programs database *\"implements an evolutionary algorithm that determines which programs will be used for future prompts.\"* (Source: BLOG)\n\n## Distributed / async pipeline and overall throughput orientation\n\n22. **It's an asyncio-based asynchronous pipeline of controller + LLM samplers + evaluation nodes, optimized for throughput.** PAPER §2.6: *\"AlphaEvolve is implemented as an asynchronous computational pipeline (using the asyncio Python library)... the asynchronous pipeline comprises a controller, LLM samplers, and evaluation nodes. The entire pipeline is optimized for throughput (rather than the speed of any one particular computation), in order to maximize the number of ideas that can be proposed and evaluated within a specific overall computation budget.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n23. **AlphaEvolve is a successor to / generalization of FunSearch.** PAPER §1 (Table 1) contrasts it with FunSearch [83] (which evolved a single function with fast ≤20-min single-CPU evaluation), whereas AlphaEvolve evolves entire code files and \"can evaluate for hours, in parallel, on accelerators.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Context note for the local build\nThe key architectural lesson transferable to the Yogi research arm (M6 population + selection): AlphaEvolve's selection is **MAP-Elites + island-model** over a program database, with a **prompt sampler** that builds prompts from sampled parents, an **LLM ensemble split by cost/quality** (cheap/fast model for breadth + expensive model for occasional depth), **diff-based mutation (SEARCH/REPLACE)** as the default mutation surface, and an **evaluation cascade** that prunes cheaply before expensive scoring. All four are in PAPER §2.\n\n### Source URLs\n- DeepMind blog: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- DeepMind white paper PDF: https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\nOne caveat: WebFetch could not parse the PDF (binary streams), so I extracted the text locally with `pdftotext` from the cached copy DeepMind served — all paper quotes above are verbatim from that extraction, with section numbers as printed in the document."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aba4c59c369d45698 (use SendMessage with to: 'aba4c59c369d45698' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 30049\ntool_uses: 10\nduration_ms: 119072</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"410e82c0-e912-4b58-a147-be90efc13944","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:28.888Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Use WebSearch and WebFetch to research the ARCHITECTURE of Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve (2025). I need specific, cited facts with exact source URLs.\n\nFocus on:\n- The evolutionary coding pipeline: ensemble of Gemini LLMs (Gemini Flash + Gemini Pro) that mutate/edit code\n- How the evolutionary loop works: population of programs, prompt sampler, LLM ensemble generating code via diffs/edits, automated evaluators scoring candidates, program database / selection\n- Why an ensemble (Flash for breadth/throughput, Pro for depth/quality)\n- That it edits whole codebases / functions, uses diff-based edits\n\nPrefer primary sources: deepmind.google blog post (search \"AlphaEvolve a Gemini-powered coding agent deepmind\"), the arxiv white paper / DeepMind white paper PDF.\n\nReturn a list of falsifiable, specific claims. Each claim MUST have its exact source URL. Quote DeepMind's wording where possible. Do not write files — return findings as your final text message.","agentId":"aba4c59c369d45698","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive primary-source material from both the DeepMind blog and the white paper PDF. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Architecture: Cited, Falsifiable Claims\n\nTwo primary sources, both DeepMind:\n- **BLOG** = DeepMind blog post: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- **PAPER** = DeepMind white paper PDF (\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\", Novikov et al.): https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\n## The LLM ensemble (which models, and why two)\n\n1. **AlphaEvolve uses an ensemble of exactly two specific Gemini models.** PAPER §2.3, \"Models used\": *\"AlphaEvolve employs an ensemble of large language models. Specifically, we utilize a combination of Gemini 2.0 Flash and Gemini 2.0 Pro.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n2. **The ensemble exists to trade throughput against quality.** PAPER §2.3: *\"This ensemble approach allows us to balance computational throughput with the quality of generated solutions.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n3. **Flash is the breadth/throughput model.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Gemini 2.0 Flash, with its lower latency, enables a higher rate of candidate generation, increasing the number of ideas explored per unit of time.\"* The blog states it more compactly: Flash *\"maximizes the breadth of ideas explored.\"* (Sources: PAPER; BLOG)\n\n4. **Pro is the depth/quality model providing occasional breakthroughs.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Concurrently, Gemini 2.0 Pro, possessing greater capabilities, provides occasional, higher-quality suggestions that can significantly advance the evolutionary search and potentially lead to breakthroughs.\"* Blog: Gemini Pro *\"provides critical depth with insightful suggestions.\"* (Sources: PAPER; BLOG)\n\n5. **The stated optimization goal of the mix.** PAPER §2.3: *\"This strategic mix optimizes the overall discovery process by maximizing the volume of evaluated ideas while retaining the potential for substantial improvements driven by the more powerful model.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n6. **AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic and improves as the base LLM improves.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Although AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic, in ablations we observe that AlphaEvolve performs increasingly better as the underlying LLM improves.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## The evolutionary loop / pipeline components\n\n7. **The pipeline has four named components plus a controller loop.** PAPER (Figure 2 / §2 architecture) names them: **Prompt sampler**, **LLMs ensemble**, **Evaluators pool**, **Program database**, driven by a **Distributed Controller Loop**. (Source: PAPER)\n\n8. **The end-to-end loop, in DeepMind's words (PAPER §2 overview):** *\"AlphaEvolve then initiates an evolutionary loop. The Prompt sampler uses programs from the Program database to construct rich prompts (Section 2.2). Given these prompts, the LLMs generate code modifications (diffs), which are applied to create new programs (Section 2.3). These are then scored by Evaluators (Section 2.4), and promising solutions are registered back into the Program database (Section 2.5), driving the iterative [process].\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n9. **The core loop is captured as three lines of pseudocode.** PAPER (Distributed Controller Loop figure):\n   ```\n   diff = llm.generate(prompt)\n   child_program = apply_diff(parent_program, diff)\n   results = evaluator.execute(child_program)\n   ```\n   (Source: PAPER)\n\n10. **Blog-level restatement of the loop.** BLOG: *\"Together, these models propose computer programs that implement algorithmic solutions as code... AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics.\"* (Source: BLOG)\n\n11. **The prompt is assembled from prior solutions sampled from the database plus instructions.** PAPER §2.2: *\"This prompt comprises multiple previously discovered solutions sampled from the program database, as well as system instructions on how to propose changes to a particular solution.\"* It also supports explicit context, stochastic formatting, rendered evaluation results, and \"meta prompt evolution.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Code editing mechanism (diffs vs. full rewrites; codebase scope)\n\n12. **The default mutation mechanism is diff-based SEARCH/REPLACE blocks.** PAPER §2.3, \"Output format\": *\"When AlphaEvolve asks an LLM to modify existing code, especially within larger codebases, it requests the changes to be provided as a sequence of diff blocks in a specific format:\"* — the format being\n    ```\n    <<<<<<< SEARCH\n    # Original code block to be found and replaced\n    =======\n    # New code block to replace the original\n    >>>>>>> REPLACE\n    ```\n    *\"the code between <<<<<<< SEARCH and ======= is the exact segment to match in the current program version... This allows for targeted updates to specific parts of the code.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n13. **Full rewrites are an alternative configuration for short code.** PAPER §2.3: *\"In cases where the code being evolved is very short, or when a complete rewrite is more appropriate than a small modification, AlphaEvolve can be configured to instruct the LLM to output the entire code block directly, rather than using the diff format.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n14. **It edits within whole files/codebases, marking blocks to evolve with `EVOLVE-BLOCK` markers.** PAPER §2.1 / Figure 3: the user provides a file \"with blocks marked for evolution\" (`# EVOLVE-BLOCK-START` ... `# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END`) plus a special `evaluate` function; *\"it requests the changes... especially within larger codebases.\"* Levels of abstraction vary by problem — single functions up to bespoke search algorithms. (Source: PAPER)\n\n15. **It makes direct changes to code (not just single functions).** PAPER abstract: *\"AlphaEvolve orchestrates an autonomous pipeline of LLMs, whose task is to improve an algorithm by making direct changes to the code.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Evaluators / scoring\n\n16. **Candidates are scored by executing a user-provided evaluation function `h` returning scalar metrics.** PAPER §2.4: *\"each new solution proposed by the LLMs is automatically evaluated. In principle, this process amounts to simply executing the user-provided evaluation function h on the generated solution.\"* The function is \"a Python function, called evaluate, with a fixed input/output signature.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n17. **Evaluation supports a cascade (cheap-to-expensive filtering).** PAPER §2.4: *\"Evaluation cascade (hypothesis testing): the user can specify ensembles of test cases of increasing difficulty, such that new solutions are evaluated on the next stage only if they achieve sufficiently promising results in all earlier stages.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n18. **Optional LLM-generated feedback can add scores (e.g., for simplicity).** PAPER §2.4: properties \"difficult to capture precisely in the user-provided evaluation function... can be graded using separate LLM calls and added to the dictionary of scores to steer evolution.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n19. **AlphaEvolve supports multi-objective optimization, which it finds helps even a single target metric.** PAPER §2.4 \"Multiple scores\": *\"we find that even if one metric is of particular interest, optimizing for multiple metrics often improves results for the single target metric.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Program database / selection algorithm\n\n20. **The selection/storage algorithm is a combination of MAP-Elites and island-based population models.** PAPER §2.5: *\"In AlphaEvolve, the evolutionary database implements an algorithm that is inspired by a combination of the MAP elites algorithm [74] and island-based population models [83, 97].\"* Its goal: *\"balancing exploration and exploitation, to continuously improve the best programs while maintaining diversity.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n21. **The blog's plainer description of the database's role:** the programs database *\"implements an evolutionary algorithm that determines which programs will be used for future prompts.\"* (Source: BLOG)\n\n## Distributed / async pipeline and overall throughput orientation\n\n22. **It's an asyncio-based asynchronous pipeline of controller + LLM samplers + evaluation nodes, optimized for throughput.** PAPER §2.6: *\"AlphaEvolve is implemented as an asynchronous computational pipeline (using the asyncio Python library)... the asynchronous pipeline comprises a controller, LLM samplers, and evaluation nodes. The entire pipeline is optimized for throughput (rather than the speed of any one particular computation), in order to maximize the number of ideas that can be proposed and evaluated within a specific overall computation budget.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n23. **AlphaEvolve is a successor to / generalization of FunSearch.** PAPER §1 (Table 1) contrasts it with FunSearch [83] (which evolved a single function with fast ≤20-min single-CPU evaluation), whereas AlphaEvolve evolves entire code files and \"can evaluate for hours, in parallel, on accelerators.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Context note for the local build\nThe key architectural lesson transferable to the Yogi research arm (M6 population + selection): AlphaEvolve's selection is **MAP-Elites + island-model** over a program database, with a **prompt sampler** that builds prompts from sampled parents, an **LLM ensemble split by cost/quality** (cheap/fast model for breadth + expensive model for occasional depth), **diff-based mutation (SEARCH/REPLACE)** as the default mutation surface, and an **evaluation cascade** that prunes cheaply before expensive scoring. All four are in PAPER §2.\n\n### Source URLs\n- DeepMind blog: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- DeepMind white paper PDF: https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\nOne caveat: WebFetch could not parse the PDF (binary streams), so I extracted the text locally with `pdftotext` from the cached copy DeepMind served — all paper quotes above are verbatim from that extraction, with section numbers as printed in the document."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":119072,"totalTokens":30049,"totalToolUseCount":10,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2298,"cache_read_input_tokens":23917,"output_tokens":3832,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2298},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3832,"cache_read_input_tokens":23917,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2298,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2298,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":5,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":5}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8fa77b85-f8e5-4d2a-b71e-6eb58af612dc","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"a6196bc9-15e3-4277-ad2a-78f316685889","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YTm6utPXCPE3dMesXMgBvG","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have everything from the primary white paper, cross-checked against the DeepMind blog and IEEE Spectrum. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n## AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Concrete Results on Mathematics and Algorithms\n\nAll numbers below are verified against the **primary DeepMind white paper** (\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\"), cross-checked against the DeepMind blog and IEEE Spectrum. The white paper is arXiv 2506.13131; the DeepMind-hosted PDF carries identical text.\n\n**Primary source URLs used:**\n- White paper PDF: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n- DeepMind blog: `https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n- IEEE Spectrum: `https://spectrum.ieee.org/deepmind-alphaevolve`\n\n---\n\n### 1. Matrix multiplication — 4×4 complex matrices (the headline result)\n\n- **AlphaEvolve multiplies two 4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications**, beating the rank-49 obtained by recursively applying **Strassen's 1969 algorithm**. This is \"the **first improvement, after 56 years**, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\" (White paper, abstract / §3.1; blog)\n  - Exact white paper quote: *\"...found an algorithm to multiply 4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications... offering the first improvement, after 56 years, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\"*\n  - The ⟨4,4,4⟩ tensor entry: best known **49** [Strassen ref 95] → AlphaEvolve **48**. (Table 2 / Table 3)\n  - Nuance the paper itself flags (footnote): algorithms using fewer than 49 multiplications existed but did not correspond to valid *tensor decompositions* (i.e., not general exact recursive algorithms). The 48 result uses complex-valued multiplications usable for exact multiplication of complex *or* real matrices.\n  - Source: white paper PDF, abstract + §3.1 + Table 2/3.\n\n- **Broader tensor-decomposition sweep:** Of **54 tensor targets** ⟨m,n,p⟩ (all m,n,p ≤ 5 plus some larger), AlphaEvolve **matched** the state of the art in **38 cases**, **surpassed** it in **14 cases**, and **fell behind** in **2 cases**. (White paper, Table 3 caption)\n  - Example improvements (best known → AlphaEvolve): ⟨3,4,6⟩ 56→54; ⟨3,5,6⟩ 70→68; ⟨2,5,6⟩ 48→47; ⟨4,5,6⟩ 93→90; ⟨2,4,5⟩ 33→32; ⟨4,4,8⟩ 98→96.\n  - Source: white paper PDF, Tables 2 and 3.\n\n### 2. ~50 open math problems — match / improve rates\n\n- AlphaEvolve was applied to **\"a large number (over 50)\"** of open problems in mathematical analysis, geometry, and combinatorics. It **matched the best-known constructions on ~75%** of them, and on **~20%** it **surpassed the SOTA and found new, provably better constructions**. (White paper §1; blog)\n  - White paper quote: *\"...match the best known constructions on ∼75% of them... On ∼20% of the problems, AlphaEvolve surpasses the SOTA and discovers new, provably better constructions.\"*\n  - IEEE Spectrum phrasing: \"for 75 percent of the problems... replicated the already known optimal solution. In 20 percent of cases, it found a new optimum that surpassed any known solution\" (remaining ~5% suboptimal).\n  - Sources: white paper PDF §1; DeepMind blog; IEEE Spectrum.\n\n### 3. Kissing number in 11 dimensions\n\n- AlphaEvolve **improved the lower bound on the 11-dimensional kissing number from 592 to 593**, by finding **593** non-zero 11-dimensional points with integral coordinates whose maximum norm is smaller than their minimum pairwise distance. (White paper §B.11 + §1; blog; IEEE Spectrum)\n  - Exact quote: *\"For d=11, the best known lower bound was 592 [31] and AlphaEvolve improved this to 593.\"*\n  - IEEE Spectrum notes the upper bound remains 868 (gap of 275).\n  - Sources: white paper PDF §B.11; DeepMind blog; IEEE Spectrum.\n\n### 4. Erdős minimum overlap problem\n\n- AlphaEvolve established a **new upper bound** for Erdős's minimum overlap problem (constant C₅). Known bounds were **0.379005 ≤ C₅ ≤ 0.380927** (upper from White, ref 107, via convex programming). AlphaEvolve improved the upper bound to **C₅ ≤ 0.380924** (\"ever so slightly better\"). (White paper §B.5)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.5.\n\n### 5. Autocorrelation / uncertainty inequalities (analysis)\n\n- **Uncertainty inequality (constant C₄, Fourier analysis):** known bounds 0.2025 ≤ C₄ ≤ 0.3523. AlphaEvolve improved the upper bound to **C₄ ≤ 0.3521**, and after incorporating a refined approach (suggested by Henry Cohn post-publication) further to **C₄ ≤ 0.3216**. (White paper §B.4)\n- **Autocorrelation inequalities:** AlphaEvolve \"improved the best known bounds on several autocorrelation inequalities\" (paper §3.2 summary lists three; detailed in §B.1–B.3). The blog/§3.2 describes these qualitatively.\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.4 and §3.2.\n\n### 6. Sums and differences of finite sets (constant C₆)\n\n- For the constant C₆ governing |A−B| vs |A+B|: AlphaEvolve found a set U₁ of size **2003** improving the lower bound to **1.1479 ≤ C₆**, and a larger set U₂ of size **54265** improving it further to **1.1584 ≤ C₆** (upper bound 4/3 ≈ 1.333). (White paper §B.6)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.6.\n\n### 7. Other geometry / packing results\n\n- **Packing unit regular hexagons into a regular hexagon:** n=11 best-known outer side **3.943 → 3.931**; n=12 **4.0 → 3.942**. (§B.7)\n- **Min ratio of max-to-min distance:** 2D, 16 points, squared ratio **12.890 → 12.889266112**; 3D, 14 points, **4.168 → 4.165849767**. (§B.8)\n- **Heilbronn problem (triangle), n=11:** SOTA min triangle area **0.036 → >0.0365**. (§B.9)\n- **Heilbronn problem (convex region):** n=13 **0.0306 → 0.0309**; n=14 **0.0277 → 0.0278**. (§B.10)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §§B.7–B.10.\n\n---\n\n**Note on AlphaTensor vs AlphaEvolve confusion (for falsification robustness):** IEEE Spectrum's framing that \"AlphaTensor had already beat the previous best… for multiplying 4×4 matrices\" refers to AlphaTensor's earlier 47-multiplication result over **GF(2)** (mod-2 arithmetic), which is *not* a general algorithm over arbitrary fields. AlphaEvolve's 48 is the first improvement over Strassen's 49 that works as a true tensor decomposition for **complex/real-valued** 4×4 matrices — which is why the paper claims \"56 years.\" Keep these two distinct when checking the claim.\n\n**Most-cited single source for nearly every number above:** the DeepMind white paper PDF (`https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`), equivalent to arXiv 2506.13131. The blog post (`https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`) independently confirms the 48-vs-49 / 56-years claim, the ~50 problems / ~75% / ~20% figures, and the 593 kissing-number configuration."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a2c2fb2f89230a0db (use SendMessage with to: 'a2c2fb2f89230a0db' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 36804\ntool_uses: 14\nduration_ms: 115328</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"14676626-8da1-4905-acad-b2cf5ddea5d2","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:35.934Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Use WebSearch and WebFetch to research the CONCRETE RESULTS on ALGORITHMS AND MATHEMATICS achieved by Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve (2025). I need specific numbers with exact source URLs.\n\nFocus on these specific claims and verify exact figures:\n- 4x4 complex-valued matrix multiplication using 48 scalar multiplications (vs Strassen's 49), the first improvement in 56 years over Strassen's 1969 algorithm\n- Advances on open math problems: applied to ~50 open problems in mathematics/analysis/geometry/combinatorics; rediscovered state-of-the-art in ~75% and improved on ~20%\n- The kissing number problem in 11 dimensions (new lower bound — find the exact number, e.g. 593)\n- Any other math results (e.g. Erdos minimum overlap, uncertainty principles, sum-difference sets)\n\nPrefer primary sources: deepmind.google blog post (\"AlphaEvolve a Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms\"), the arxiv white paper PDF (arxiv 2506.13131 or the DeepMind white paper). Cross-check numbers across sources.\n\nReturn a list of falsifiable, specific claims with exact numbers. Each claim MUST have its exact source URL. Do not write files — return findings as your final text message.","agentId":"a2c2fb2f89230a0db","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have everything from the primary white paper, cross-checked against the DeepMind blog and IEEE Spectrum. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n## AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Concrete Results on Mathematics and Algorithms\n\nAll numbers below are verified against the **primary DeepMind white paper** (\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\"), cross-checked against the DeepMind blog and IEEE Spectrum. The white paper is arXiv 2506.13131; the DeepMind-hosted PDF carries identical text.\n\n**Primary source URLs used:**\n- White paper PDF: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n- DeepMind blog: `https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n- IEEE Spectrum: `https://spectrum.ieee.org/deepmind-alphaevolve`\n\n---\n\n### 1. Matrix multiplication — 4×4 complex matrices (the headline result)\n\n- **AlphaEvolve multiplies two 4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications**, beating the rank-49 obtained by recursively applying **Strassen's 1969 algorithm**. This is \"the **first improvement, after 56 years**, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\" (White paper, abstract / §3.1; blog)\n  - Exact white paper quote: *\"...found an algorithm to multiply 4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications... offering the first improvement, after 56 years, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\"*\n  - The ⟨4,4,4⟩ tensor entry: best known **49** [Strassen ref 95] → AlphaEvolve **48**. (Table 2 / Table 3)\n  - Nuance the paper itself flags (footnote): algorithms using fewer than 49 multiplications existed but did not correspond to valid *tensor decompositions* (i.e., not general exact recursive algorithms). The 48 result uses complex-valued multiplications usable for exact multiplication of complex *or* real matrices.\n  - Source: white paper PDF, abstract + §3.1 + Table 2/3.\n\n- **Broader tensor-decomposition sweep:** Of **54 tensor targets** ⟨m,n,p⟩ (all m,n,p ≤ 5 plus some larger), AlphaEvolve **matched** the state of the art in **38 cases**, **surpassed** it in **14 cases**, and **fell behind** in **2 cases**. (White paper, Table 3 caption)\n  - Example improvements (best known → AlphaEvolve): ⟨3,4,6⟩ 56→54; ⟨3,5,6⟩ 70→68; ⟨2,5,6⟩ 48→47; ⟨4,5,6⟩ 93→90; ⟨2,4,5⟩ 33→32; ⟨4,4,8⟩ 98→96.\n  - Source: white paper PDF, Tables 2 and 3.\n\n### 2. ~50 open math problems — match / improve rates\n\n- AlphaEvolve was applied to **\"a large number (over 50)\"** of open problems in mathematical analysis, geometry, and combinatorics. It **matched the best-known constructions on ~75%** of them, and on **~20%** it **surpassed the SOTA and found new, provably better constructions**. (White paper §1; blog)\n  - White paper quote: *\"...match the best known constructions on ∼75% of them... On ∼20% of the problems, AlphaEvolve surpasses the SOTA and discovers new, provably better constructions.\"*\n  - IEEE Spectrum phrasing: \"for 75 percent of the problems... replicated the already known optimal solution. In 20 percent of cases, it found a new optimum that surpassed any known solution\" (remaining ~5% suboptimal).\n  - Sources: white paper PDF §1; DeepMind blog; IEEE Spectrum.\n\n### 3. Kissing number in 11 dimensions\n\n- AlphaEvolve **improved the lower bound on the 11-dimensional kissing number from 592 to 593**, by finding **593** non-zero 11-dimensional points with integral coordinates whose maximum norm is smaller than their minimum pairwise distance. (White paper §B.11 + §1; blog; IEEE Spectrum)\n  - Exact quote: *\"For d=11, the best known lower bound was 592 [31] and AlphaEvolve improved this to 593.\"*\n  - IEEE Spectrum notes the upper bound remains 868 (gap of 275).\n  - Sources: white paper PDF §B.11; DeepMind blog; IEEE Spectrum.\n\n### 4. Erdős minimum overlap problem\n\n- AlphaEvolve established a **new upper bound** for Erdős's minimum overlap problem (constant C₅). Known bounds were **0.379005 ≤ C₅ ≤ 0.380927** (upper from White, ref 107, via convex programming). AlphaEvolve improved the upper bound to **C₅ ≤ 0.380924** (\"ever so slightly better\"). (White paper §B.5)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.5.\n\n### 5. Autocorrelation / uncertainty inequalities (analysis)\n\n- **Uncertainty inequality (constant C₄, Fourier analysis):** known bounds 0.2025 ≤ C₄ ≤ 0.3523. AlphaEvolve improved the upper bound to **C₄ ≤ 0.3521**, and after incorporating a refined approach (suggested by Henry Cohn post-publication) further to **C₄ ≤ 0.3216**. (White paper §B.4)\n- **Autocorrelation inequalities:** AlphaEvolve \"improved the best known bounds on several autocorrelation inequalities\" (paper §3.2 summary lists three; detailed in §B.1–B.3). The blog/§3.2 describes these qualitatively.\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.4 and §3.2.\n\n### 6. Sums and differences of finite sets (constant C₆)\n\n- For the constant C₆ governing |A−B| vs |A+B|: AlphaEvolve found a set U₁ of size **2003** improving the lower bound to **1.1479 ≤ C₆**, and a larger set U₂ of size **54265** improving it further to **1.1584 ≤ C₆** (upper bound 4/3 ≈ 1.333). (White paper §B.6)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.6.\n\n### 7. Other geometry / packing results\n\n- **Packing unit regular hexagons into a regular hexagon:** n=11 best-known outer side **3.943 → 3.931**; n=12 **4.0 → 3.942**. (§B.7)\n- **Min ratio of max-to-min distance:** 2D, 16 points, squared ratio **12.890 → 12.889266112**; 3D, 14 points, **4.168 → 4.165849767**. (§B.8)\n- **Heilbronn problem (triangle), n=11:** SOTA min triangle area **0.036 → >0.0365**. (§B.9)\n- **Heilbronn problem (convex region):** n=13 **0.0306 → 0.0309**; n=14 **0.0277 → 0.0278**. (§B.10)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §§B.7–B.10.\n\n---\n\n**Note on AlphaTensor vs AlphaEvolve confusion (for falsification robustness):** IEEE Spectrum's framing that \"AlphaTensor had already beat the previous best… for multiplying 4×4 matrices\" refers to AlphaTensor's earlier 47-multiplication result over **GF(2)** (mod-2 arithmetic), which is *not* a general algorithm over arbitrary fields. AlphaEvolve's 48 is the first improvement over Strassen's 49 that works as a true tensor decomposition for **complex/real-valued** 4×4 matrices — which is why the paper claims \"56 years.\" Keep these two distinct when checking the claim.\n\n**Most-cited single source for nearly every number above:** the DeepMind white paper PDF (`https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`), equivalent to arXiv 2506.13131. The blog post (`https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`) independently confirms the 48-vs-49 / 56-years claim, the ~50 problems / ~75% / ~20% figures, and the 593 kissing-number configuration."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":115328,"totalTokens":36804,"totalToolUseCount":14,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1342,"cache_read_input_tokens":32384,"output_tokens":3076,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1342},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3076,"cache_read_input_tokens":32384,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1342,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1342,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":9,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":5}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a6196bc9-15e3-4277-ad2a-78f316685889","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"87376167-e5da-4438-a204-cfac602dcb41","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FMg3mfjJ9bVH7CjeGhq6UD","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong primary-source material plus VentureBeat and TechCrunch for secondary framing. I have everything needed. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025): The Role of the Verifier / Evaluation Function\n\nAll claims below are falsifiable and tied to exact source URLs. The two primary sources are the DeepMind white paper PDF and the DeepMind blog post.\n\n**Primary sources:**\n- White paper PDF: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` (title: *\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\"*)\n- Blog post: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n---\n\n## A. The verifier IS the core mechanism (every candidate is machine-scored)\n\n**Claim 1 — AlphaEvolve only tackles problems with machine-gradable solutions; the user must supply an automated assessor.**\n> \"Since AlphaEvolve tackles problems with machine-gradeable solutions, the user must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing generated solutions.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.1 Task specification — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n\nNote the exact DeepMind spelling is **\"machine-gradeable\"** (with the extra \"e\").\n\n**Claim 2 — The verifier is a function h mapping a solution to a set of scalar metrics, which are maximized.**\n> \"This mechanism takes the form of a function ℎ mapping a solution to a set of scalar evaluation metrics. By convention, these metrics are maximized. In our current setup, ℎ is typically implemented as a Python function, called evaluate, with a fixed input/output signature, returning a dictionary of scalars.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.1 — same URL.\n\n**Claim 3 — Evaluation = simply executing the user-provided function h on each candidate.**\n> \"each new solution proposed by the LLMs is automatically evaluated. In principle, this process amounts to simply executing the user-provided evaluation function ℎ on the generated solution.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.4 Evaluation — same URL.\n\n**Claim 4 — The evolutionary loop is driven entirely by the score from automated metrics.**\n> The orchestrator is \"an evolutionary algorithm that gradually develops programs that improve the score on the automated evaluation metrics associated with the task.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~123) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 5 — Blog post phrasing: AlphaEvolve \"verifies, runs and scores\" via automated metrics.**\n> \"AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics. These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n**Claim 6 — The system pairs the LLM with \"automated evaluators that verify answers.\"**\n> AlphaEvolve \"pairs the creative problem-solving capabilities of our Gemini models with automated evaluators that verify answers, and uses an evolutionary framework to improve upon the most promising ideas.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — same URL.\n\n---\n\n## B. Why this is a FUNDAMENTAL constraint (DeepMind's own caveats, verbatim)\n\n**Claim 7 — DeepMind explicitly frames the automated metric as both the advantage AND the limitation (this is the key caveat, stated up front in the paper).**\n> \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, intro / Table 1 region (line ~88) — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n\n**Claim 8 — The \"main limitation,\" verbatim from the paper's conclusion: it only handles problems for which an automated evaluator can be devised.**\n> \"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, Conclusion / Limitations (line ~1896) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 9 — Domain focus is a direct consequence of the constraint: math, CS, system optimization are chosen precisely because they permit automated metrics.**\n> \"Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~90) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 10 — Blog post echoes the same scoping rationale.**\n> \"This makes AlphaEvolve particularly helpful in a broad range of domains where progress can be clearly and systematically measured, like in math and computer science.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n---\n\n## C. What classes of problems this EXCLUDES\n\n**Claim 11 — Tasks requiring manual experimentation are out of scope (verbatim, paper intro).** See Claim 7: \"...it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~89) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 12 — Natural sciences / wet-lab style work where experiments cannot be simulated or automated are excluded.** See Claim 8: \"...there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~1898) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 13 — Non-numerical / non-algorithmic problems are a poor fit (secondary-source framing of the constraint).**\n> \"Because AlphaEvolve can only solve problems that it can self-evaluate, the system can only work with certain types of problems.\" and \"In another major limitation, AlphaEvolve can only describe solutions as algorithms, making it a poor fit for problems that aren't numerical.\" and \"They must also provide a mechanism for automatically assessing the system's answers in the form of a formula.\"\nSource: TechCrunch — `https://techcrunch.com/2025/05/14/deepmind-claims-its-newest-ai-tool-is-a-whiz-at-math-and-science-problems/`\n\n**Claim 14 — Subjective / qualitative outputs that cannot be captured in the programmatic score: DeepMind only partially addresses these, and explicitly has NOT optimized for it.**\n> \"While AlphaEvolve does allow for LLM-provided evaluation of ideas, this is not a setting we have optimized for.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, Conclusion (line ~1899) — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\nThis is the important nuance: AlphaEvolve has an *optional* \"LLM-generated feedback\" mechanism for qualities \"difficult to capture precisely in the user-provided evaluation function ℎ\" (e.g. program simplicity) — but DeepMind states it is not a setting they optimized for, and the core loop still requires the machine score. (Optional LLM-feedback mechanism described in §2.4, same URL.)\n\n---\n\n## D. Supporting detail on the evaluator's machinery (reinforces that scoring is programmatic/automated)\n\n**Claim 15 — Evaluation can be a multi-stage automated cascade (hypothesis testing) and can run for ~100 compute-hours per candidate, parallelized.**\n> \"Evaluation cascade (hypothesis testing): the user can specify ensembles of test cases of increasing difficulty...\" and \"the sample efficiency of AlphaEvolve makes it feasible to spend on the order of 100 compute-hours to evaluate any new solution.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.4 — same URL.\n\n**Claim 16 — Independent technical write-up confirms the per-iteration accept/reject is gated on the user-supplied evaluate function returning machine-gradable metrics.**\n> Every iteration \"is accepted or rejected based on a user-supplied 'evaluate' function that returns machine-gradable metrics.\"\nSource: VentureBeat — `https://venturebeat.com/ai/googles-alphaevolve-the-ai-agent-that-reclaimed-0-7-of-googles-compute-and-how-to-copy-it`\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the load-bearing point\n\nDeepMind itself states the constraint in two places almost identically: the evaluation metric is \"a key advantage\" but \"also a limitation,\" and the \"main limitation … is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator.\" The verifier (the `evaluate` function `h` returning a dict of scalars) is not an optional add-on — it is the selection signal for the entire evolutionary loop. Anything lacking a programmatic score (subjective/qualitative outputs, wet-lab/physical experimentation, non-numerical/non-algorithmic problems) is out of scope by construction; the only escape hatch DeepMind offers is optional LLM-as-judge feedback, which they explicitly note is \"not a setting we have optimized for.\"\n\n**The strongest verbatim DeepMind caveats to quote** are Claim 7 and Claim 8 (both from the white paper PDF), plus the \"machine-gradeable solutions … must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing\" line in Claim 1.\n\n(One caveat on secondary sources: I could not retrieve a working Ars Technica URL for this story; TechCrunch and VentureBeat are used instead and both directly corroborate the constraint framing.)"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a694ec9ee8d30ccac (use SendMessage with to: 'a694ec9ee8d30ccac' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 29901\ntool_uses: 12\nduration_ms: 131716</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"03542f58-b8c1-4a01-a334-667b400f0916","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:45.988Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Use WebSearch and WebFetch to research the ROLE OF THE VERIFIER / EVALUATION FUNCTION in Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve (2025). I need specific, cited facts with exact source URLs.\n\nFocus on:\n- AlphaEvolve only works on problems with a machine-gradable / automatically-verifiable objective function (an automated evaluator that returns a score)\n- Why this is a fundamental constraint of the system\n- What classes of problems this EXCLUDES (problems that cannot be automatically evaluated, e.g. subjective/qualitative outputs, problems requiring manual experimentation or wet-lab work, anything without a programmatic scoring metric)\n- The exact phrasing DeepMind uses about \"automated evaluation metrics\", \"machine-gradable\", \"verifier\", \"evaluation function\"\n\nPrefer primary sources: deepmind.google blog post (\"AlphaEvolve a Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms\"), the arxiv white paper / DeepMind white paper PDF. Also credible coverage (Ars Technica, MIT Tech Review, etc.) for the framing of the constraint.\n\nReturn a list of falsifiable, specific claims. Each claim MUST have its exact source URL. Quote DeepMind's own caveats verbatim where possible. Do not write files — return findings as your final text message.","agentId":"a694ec9ee8d30ccac","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong primary-source material plus VentureBeat and TechCrunch for secondary framing. I have everything needed. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025): The Role of the Verifier / Evaluation Function\n\nAll claims below are falsifiable and tied to exact source URLs. The two primary sources are the DeepMind white paper PDF and the DeepMind blog post.\n\n**Primary sources:**\n- White paper PDF: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` (title: *\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\"*)\n- Blog post: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n---\n\n## A. The verifier IS the core mechanism (every candidate is machine-scored)\n\n**Claim 1 — AlphaEvolve only tackles problems with machine-gradable solutions; the user must supply an automated assessor.**\n> \"Since AlphaEvolve tackles problems with machine-gradeable solutions, the user must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing generated solutions.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.1 Task specification — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n\nNote the exact DeepMind spelling is **\"machine-gradeable\"** (with the extra \"e\").\n\n**Claim 2 — The verifier is a function h mapping a solution to a set of scalar metrics, which are maximized.**\n> \"This mechanism takes the form of a function ℎ mapping a solution to a set of scalar evaluation metrics. By convention, these metrics are maximized. In our current setup, ℎ is typically implemented as a Python function, called evaluate, with a fixed input/output signature, returning a dictionary of scalars.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.1 — same URL.\n\n**Claim 3 — Evaluation = simply executing the user-provided function h on each candidate.**\n> \"each new solution proposed by the LLMs is automatically evaluated. In principle, this process amounts to simply executing the user-provided evaluation function ℎ on the generated solution.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.4 Evaluation — same URL.\n\n**Claim 4 — The evolutionary loop is driven entirely by the score from automated metrics.**\n> The orchestrator is \"an evolutionary algorithm that gradually develops programs that improve the score on the automated evaluation metrics associated with the task.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~123) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 5 — Blog post phrasing: AlphaEvolve \"verifies, runs and scores\" via automated metrics.**\n> \"AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics. These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n**Claim 6 — The system pairs the LLM with \"automated evaluators that verify answers.\"**\n> AlphaEvolve \"pairs the creative problem-solving capabilities of our Gemini models with automated evaluators that verify answers, and uses an evolutionary framework to improve upon the most promising ideas.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — same URL.\n\n---\n\n## B. Why this is a FUNDAMENTAL constraint (DeepMind's own caveats, verbatim)\n\n**Claim 7 — DeepMind explicitly frames the automated metric as both the advantage AND the limitation (this is the key caveat, stated up front in the paper).**\n> \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, intro / Table 1 region (line ~88) — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n\n**Claim 8 — The \"main limitation,\" verbatim from the paper's conclusion: it only handles problems for which an automated evaluator can be devised.**\n> \"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, Conclusion / Limitations (line ~1896) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 9 — Domain focus is a direct consequence of the constraint: math, CS, system optimization are chosen precisely because they permit automated metrics.**\n> \"Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~90) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 10 — Blog post echoes the same scoping rationale.**\n> \"This makes AlphaEvolve particularly helpful in a broad range of domains where progress can be clearly and systematically measured, like in math and computer science.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n---\n\n## C. What classes of problems this EXCLUDES\n\n**Claim 11 — Tasks requiring manual experimentation are out of scope (verbatim, paper intro).** See Claim 7: \"...it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~89) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 12 — Natural sciences / wet-lab style work where experiments cannot be simulated or automated are excluded.** See Claim 8: \"...there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~1898) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 13 — Non-numerical / non-algorithmic problems are a poor fit (secondary-source framing of the constraint).**\n> \"Because AlphaEvolve can only solve problems that it can self-evaluate, the system can only work with certain types of problems.\" and \"In another major limitation, AlphaEvolve can only describe solutions as algorithms, making it a poor fit for problems that aren't numerical.\" and \"They must also provide a mechanism for automatically assessing the system's answers in the form of a formula.\"\nSource: TechCrunch — `https://techcrunch.com/2025/05/14/deepmind-claims-its-newest-ai-tool-is-a-whiz-at-math-and-science-problems/`\n\n**Claim 14 — Subjective / qualitative outputs that cannot be captured in the programmatic score: DeepMind only partially addresses these, and explicitly has NOT optimized for it.**\n> \"While AlphaEvolve does allow for LLM-provided evaluation of ideas, this is not a setting we have optimized for.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, Conclusion (line ~1899) — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\nThis is the important nuance: AlphaEvolve has an *optional* \"LLM-generated feedback\" mechanism for qualities \"difficult to capture precisely in the user-provided evaluation function ℎ\" (e.g. program simplicity) — but DeepMind states it is not a setting they optimized for, and the core loop still requires the machine score. (Optional LLM-feedback mechanism described in §2.4, same URL.)\n\n---\n\n## D. Supporting detail on the evaluator's machinery (reinforces that scoring is programmatic/automated)\n\n**Claim 15 — Evaluation can be a multi-stage automated cascade (hypothesis testing) and can run for ~100 compute-hours per candidate, parallelized.**\n> \"Evaluation cascade (hypothesis testing): the user can specify ensembles of test cases of increasing difficulty...\" and \"the sample efficiency of AlphaEvolve makes it feasible to spend on the order of 100 compute-hours to evaluate any new solution.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.4 — same URL.\n\n**Claim 16 — Independent technical write-up confirms the per-iteration accept/reject is gated on the user-supplied evaluate function returning machine-gradable metrics.**\n> Every iteration \"is accepted or rejected based on a user-supplied 'evaluate' function that returns machine-gradable metrics.\"\nSource: VentureBeat — `https://venturebeat.com/ai/googles-alphaevolve-the-ai-agent-that-reclaimed-0-7-of-googles-compute-and-how-to-copy-it`\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the load-bearing point\n\nDeepMind itself states the constraint in two places almost identically: the evaluation metric is \"a key advantage\" but \"also a limitation,\" and the \"main limitation … is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator.\" The verifier (the `evaluate` function `h` returning a dict of scalars) is not an optional add-on — it is the selection signal for the entire evolutionary loop. Anything lacking a programmatic score (subjective/qualitative outputs, wet-lab/physical experimentation, non-numerical/non-algorithmic problems) is out of scope by construction; the only escape hatch DeepMind offers is optional LLM-as-judge feedback, which they explicitly note is \"not a setting we have optimized for.\"\n\n**The strongest verbatim DeepMind caveats to quote** are Claim 7 and Claim 8 (both from the white paper PDF), plus the \"machine-gradeable solutions … must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing\" line in Claim 1.\n\n(One caveat on secondary sources: I could not retrieve a working Ars Technica URL for this story; TechCrunch and VentureBeat are used instead and both directly corroborate the constraint framing.)"}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":131716,"totalTokens":29901,"totalToolUseCount":12,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1370,"cache_read_input_tokens":24611,"output_tokens":3597,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1370},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":323,"output_tokens":3597,"cache_read_input_tokens":24611,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1370,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1370,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":4,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":8}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"87376167-e5da-4438-a204-cfac602dcb41","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2a8d5bab-5e03-4247-b4a8-6756acc07220","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RBehCJCCisSrV9RUbXutVm","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything needed, including the precise characterization that AlphaEvolve optimizes kernels/tiling (training-infrastructure speed) — not the LLM's weights — and that distilling its outputs into the base model is only described as a future step. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Limitations / What It Cannot Do\n\nAll quotes below are verbatim. Two primary sources:\n- **White paper PDF** (DeepMind-hosted): `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` — also on arXiv as **2506.13131** (`https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.13131`, HTML mirror `https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2506.13131`).\n- **Blog post**: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n## Falsifiable claims with citations\n\n### 1. The main stated limitation: it requires an automated evaluator; problems needing manual experimentation are OUT OF SCOPE\nThis is DeepMind's single most explicit caveat, stated twice.\n\n- **White paper, §6 Discussion (the \"main limitation\" sentence), verbatim:**\n  > \"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\n  Source: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` (§6 Discussion, p. 20).\n\n- **White paper, early section (Section 2 / Table 1 discussion), verbatim:**\n  > \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope. Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"\n  Source: same PDF (p. 3, around Table 1).\n\n### 2. Scope is defined as problems whose solution \"can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified\"\n- **Blog post, verbatim:**\n  > \"While AlphaEvolve is currently being applied across math and computing, its general nature means it can be applied to any problem whose solution can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified.\"\n  Source: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n- **Blog post**, on the necessity of automated metrics, verbatim:\n  > \"These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"\n  Source: same blog URL.\n\n### 3. AlphaEvolve does NOT modify Gemini's weights — it improves *infrastructure / training kernels*, not the model itself\nDeepMind never claims it edits or retrains the base LLM's parameters. What it improved about the LLM pipeline is the **matrix-multiplication kernel tiling** used to *train* Gemini (a speed/throughput optimization), with correctness preserved by construction:\n\n- **White paper, §3.3.2 \"Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering,\" verbatim:**\n  > \"The kernel's correctness is maintained by construction because AlphaEvolve is optimizing the tiling strategy for this kernel rather than altering [the computation]…\"\n  > \"…average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic…\"\n  Source: PDF §3.3.2 (p. 16–17).\n\n- The blog frames this as improving how Gemini is *trained/served*, not the weights:\n  > \"By finding smarter ways to divide a large matrix multiplication operation into more manageable subproblems, it sped up this vital kernel in Gemini's architecture by 23%, leading to a 1% reduction in Gemini's training time.\"\n  Source: blog URL above.\n\nThis supports the claim \"AlphaEvolve is not recursive self-improvement of the model itself.\" Corroborated by secondary analysis (Google Cloud Community / Medium): \"AlphaEvolve has improved the matrix multiplication kernel used to train the Gemini models… this is optimization of the training infrastructure and kernels, not direct improvement of the LLM's weights or core model parameters.\" Source: `https://medium.com/google-cloud/overcoming-llm-performance-plateau-alphaevolves-evolutionary-approach-to-continuous-gemini-e5a22c64b540`\n\n### 4. Improving the base LLM with AlphaEvolve's outputs is explicitly framed as FUTURE WORK (distillation), not something the system does\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"…a natural next step will be to consider distilling the AlphaEvolve-augmented performance of the base LLMs into the next generation of the base models. This can have intrinsic value and also, likely, uplift the next version of AlphaEvolve.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\n- And the self-improvement-of-infrastructure loop is described as **moderate and slow (months)**, verbatim:\n  > \"Beyond distillation, it is also intriguing that AlphaEvolve can make practical discoveries that increase the efficiency of its own infrastructure and of (future versions of) its base LLMs. Currently, the gains are moderate and the feedback loops for improving the next version of AlphaEvolve are on the order of months.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\nThis is the strongest verbatim DeepMind material against a \"fast recursive self-improvement / takeoff\" reading: the loop closes only via human-run future training generations, on a months-long cadence, with moderate gains.\n\n### 5. AlphaEvolve is positioned as a \"test-time compute agent\" enhancing the base LLM's *capability at inference*, not changing the model\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"AlphaEvolve can also be seen as a test-time compute agent that, through its evolutionary procedure, significantly enhances the capability of the base LLM (compared to, e.g., repeated sampling).\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\nThe enhancement is to *outputs via search at test time*, not to weights — reinforcing claims #3 and #4.\n\n### 6. LLM-as-judge evaluation is allowed but explicitly NOT optimized for — i.e. the system in practice depends on programmatic evaluators\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"While AlphaEvolve does allow for LLM-provided evaluation of ideas, this is not a setting we have optimized for. However, concurrent work shows this is possible [34], and a natural step would be to link the two settings, with LLMs providing feedback on high-level ideas before transitioning to an implementation stage, for which machine feedback is available through code execution.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\n### 7. Human-defined problems and metrics constrain autonomy (secondary framing of the same limitation)\nDeepMind's primary sources don't claim autonomy; secondary commentary makes the boundary explicit: AlphaEvolve \"cannot independently identify or define new challenges\" and \"relies on human-defined problems and evaluation metrics,\" restricting its autonomy. Sources: `https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/` and `https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/what-is-alphaevolve-google-ai-self-improvement-2`\n\n### 8. On the \"recursive self-improvement / AGI\" framing — contested, and DeepMind itself does not claim AGI\n- DeepMind's own materials make **no AGI claim** and **no recursive-self-improvement claim**; the closest is the cautious \"increase the efficiency of its own infrastructure… gains are moderate… feedback loops… on the order of months\" (claim #4).\n- Secondary coverage frames it at most as a \"careful/measured\" early form of recursive self-improvement and \"a step toward AGI,\" not AGI itself. Sources: `https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/`, `https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/alpha-evolve-ai-recursive-learning/`\n\n## Notes on sourcing\n- The white-paper page numbers above are from the DeepMind-hosted PDF; the identical text is in arXiv 2506.13131 (§6 \"Discussion\" and the Section 2 paragraph following Table 1).\n- I could not surface dedicated AlphaEvolve limitations coverage from MIT Tech Review / Ars Technica / IEEE Spectrum in the available US search results; the strongest expert-limitation framing came directly from DeepMind's own §6 Discussion plus unite.ai, HPCwire/AIwire (`https://www.hpcwire.com/2025/06/02/can-alphaevolve-change-how-we-solve-problems-a-look-inside-deepminds-latest-breakthrough/`), and the Google Cloud Community write-up. The primary-source quotes (claims #1–#6) are the load-bearing, verbatim, falsifiable ones."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a314bc97408580996 (use SendMessage with to: 'a314bc97408580996' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 27367\ntool_uses: 11\nduration_ms: 113254</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"2f8ee61b-cf31-4c4c-9973-91fd200368b7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:46.176Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Use WebSearch and WebFetch to research the LIMITATIONS / WHAT ALPHAEVOLVE CANNOT DO for Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve (2025). I need specific, cited facts with exact source URLs and verbatim quotes.\n\nFocus on:\n- AlphaEvolve does NOT improve its own underlying LLMs / does not modify Gemini's weights (it is not recursive self-improvement of the model itself)\n- It REQUIRES an automated verifier/evaluator — it cannot be applied to problems lacking automated evaluation\n- The main limitation stated by DeepMind: it handles problems whose solutions can be \"described as algorithms\" and \"automatically evaluated\"; problems requiring manual experimentation are excluded\n- Any DeepMind caveats about scope, generality, future work\n- Any commentary on whether this is/isn't \"recursive self-improvement\" or AGI\n\nPrefer primary sources: deepmind.google blog post (\"AlphaEvolve a Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms\"), the arxiv/DeepMind white paper PDF (look at the Limitations and Conclusion sections). Also credible coverage (MIT Tech Review, Ars Technica, IEEE Spectrum) for how experts framed the limits.\n\nReturn a list of falsifiable, specific claims. Each claim MUST have its exact source URL. Quote DeepMind's own caveats VERBATIM where possible. Do not write files — return findings as your final text message.","agentId":"a314bc97408580996","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything needed, including the precise characterization that AlphaEvolve optimizes kernels/tiling (training-infrastructure speed) — not the LLM's weights — and that distilling its outputs into the base model is only described as a future step. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Limitations / What It Cannot Do\n\nAll quotes below are verbatim. Two primary sources:\n- **White paper PDF** (DeepMind-hosted): `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` — also on arXiv as **2506.13131** (`https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.13131`, HTML mirror `https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2506.13131`).\n- **Blog post**: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n## Falsifiable claims with citations\n\n### 1. The main stated limitation: it requires an automated evaluator; problems needing manual experimentation are OUT OF SCOPE\nThis is DeepMind's single most explicit caveat, stated twice.\n\n- **White paper, §6 Discussion (the \"main limitation\" sentence), verbatim:**\n  > \"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\n  Source: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` (§6 Discussion, p. 20).\n\n- **White paper, early section (Section 2 / Table 1 discussion), verbatim:**\n  > \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope. Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"\n  Source: same PDF (p. 3, around Table 1).\n\n### 2. Scope is defined as problems whose solution \"can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified\"\n- **Blog post, verbatim:**\n  > \"While AlphaEvolve is currently being applied across math and computing, its general nature means it can be applied to any problem whose solution can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified.\"\n  Source: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n- **Blog post**, on the necessity of automated metrics, verbatim:\n  > \"These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"\n  Source: same blog URL.\n\n### 3. AlphaEvolve does NOT modify Gemini's weights — it improves *infrastructure / training kernels*, not the model itself\nDeepMind never claims it edits or retrains the base LLM's parameters. What it improved about the LLM pipeline is the **matrix-multiplication kernel tiling** used to *train* Gemini (a speed/throughput optimization), with correctness preserved by construction:\n\n- **White paper, §3.3.2 \"Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering,\" verbatim:**\n  > \"The kernel's correctness is maintained by construction because AlphaEvolve is optimizing the tiling strategy for this kernel rather than altering [the computation]…\"\n  > \"…average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic…\"\n  Source: PDF §3.3.2 (p. 16–17).\n\n- The blog frames this as improving how Gemini is *trained/served*, not the weights:\n  > \"By finding smarter ways to divide a large matrix multiplication operation into more manageable subproblems, it sped up this vital kernel in Gemini's architecture by 23%, leading to a 1% reduction in Gemini's training time.\"\n  Source: blog URL above.\n\nThis supports the claim \"AlphaEvolve is not recursive self-improvement of the model itself.\" Corroborated by secondary analysis (Google Cloud Community / Medium): \"AlphaEvolve has improved the matrix multiplication kernel used to train the Gemini models… this is optimization of the training infrastructure and kernels, not direct improvement of the LLM's weights or core model parameters.\" Source: `https://medium.com/google-cloud/overcoming-llm-performance-plateau-alphaevolves-evolutionary-approach-to-continuous-gemini-e5a22c64b540`\n\n### 4. Improving the base LLM with AlphaEvolve's outputs is explicitly framed as FUTURE WORK (distillation), not something the system does\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"…a natural next step will be to consider distilling the AlphaEvolve-augmented performance of the base LLMs into the next generation of the base models. This can have intrinsic value and also, likely, uplift the next version of AlphaEvolve.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\n- And the self-improvement-of-infrastructure loop is described as **moderate and slow (months)**, verbatim:\n  > \"Beyond distillation, it is also intriguing that AlphaEvolve can make practical discoveries that increase the efficiency of its own infrastructure and of (future versions of) its base LLMs. Currently, the gains are moderate and the feedback loops for improving the next version of AlphaEvolve are on the order of months.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\nThis is the strongest verbatim DeepMind material against a \"fast recursive self-improvement / takeoff\" reading: the loop closes only via human-run future training generations, on a months-long cadence, with moderate gains.\n\n### 5. AlphaEvolve is positioned as a \"test-time compute agent\" enhancing the base LLM's *capability at inference*, not changing the model\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"AlphaEvolve can also be seen as a test-time compute agent that, through its evolutionary procedure, significantly enhances the capability of the base LLM (compared to, e.g., repeated sampling).\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\nThe enhancement is to *outputs via search at test time*, not to weights — reinforcing claims #3 and #4.\n\n### 6. LLM-as-judge evaluation is allowed but explicitly NOT optimized for — i.e. the system in practice depends on programmatic evaluators\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"While AlphaEvolve does allow for LLM-provided evaluation of ideas, this is not a setting we have optimized for. However, concurrent work shows this is possible [34], and a natural step would be to link the two settings, with LLMs providing feedback on high-level ideas before transitioning to an implementation stage, for which machine feedback is available through code execution.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\n### 7. Human-defined problems and metrics constrain autonomy (secondary framing of the same limitation)\nDeepMind's primary sources don't claim autonomy; secondary commentary makes the boundary explicit: AlphaEvolve \"cannot independently identify or define new challenges\" and \"relies on human-defined problems and evaluation metrics,\" restricting its autonomy. Sources: `https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/` and `https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/what-is-alphaevolve-google-ai-self-improvement-2`\n\n### 8. On the \"recursive self-improvement / AGI\" framing — contested, and DeepMind itself does not claim AGI\n- DeepMind's own materials make **no AGI claim** and **no recursive-self-improvement claim**; the closest is the cautious \"increase the efficiency of its own infrastructure… gains are moderate… feedback loops… on the order of months\" (claim #4).\n- Secondary coverage frames it at most as a \"careful/measured\" early form of recursive self-improvement and \"a step toward AGI,\" not AGI itself. Sources: `https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/`, `https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/alpha-evolve-ai-recursive-learning/`\n\n## Notes on sourcing\n- The white-paper page numbers above are from the DeepMind-hosted PDF; the identical text is in arXiv 2506.13131 (§6 \"Discussion\" and the Section 2 paragraph following Table 1).\n- I could not surface dedicated AlphaEvolve limitations coverage from MIT Tech Review / Ars Technica / IEEE Spectrum in the available US search results; the strongest expert-limitation framing came directly from DeepMind's own §6 Discussion plus unite.ai, HPCwire/AIwire (`https://www.hpcwire.com/2025/06/02/can-alphaevolve-change-how-we-solve-problems-a-look-inside-deepminds-latest-breakthrough/`), and the Google Cloud Community write-up. The primary-source quotes (claims #1–#6) are the load-bearing, verbatim, falsifiable ones."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":113254,"totalTokens":27367,"totalToolUseCount":11,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1006,"cache_read_input_tokens":23098,"output_tokens":3261,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1006},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3261,"cache_read_input_tokens":23098,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1006,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1006,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":4,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":7}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2a8d5bab-5e03-4247-b4a8-6756acc07220","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2f8ee61b-cf31-4c4c-9973-91fd200368b7","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa47f8eb58a90b448","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Gzo4nmPtmLZgsc6tj9CtrC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All five angles returned strong primary-source material from the DeepMind white paper and blog. The claims are well-cited and cross-checked. I have enough verified material to synthesize the final report. No claims need killing; a few have flagged nuances (32% vs 32.5%, AlphaTensor confusion, TPU result also caught by synthesis tools) that I'll preserve.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Cited, Falsifiable Claims\n\n**Primary sources** (both DeepMind, used throughout):\n- **BLOG**: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- **PAPER** (white paper PDF, = arXiv 2506.13131): https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n- arXiv abstract page: https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.13131\n\n---\n\n## 1. Architecture — evolutionary coding pipeline + Gemini ensemble + automated evaluators\n\n**A1.** AlphaEvolve uses an ensemble of exactly two models: **Gemini 2.0 Flash + Gemini 2.0 Pro**. *\"AlphaEvolve employs an ensemble of large language models. Specifically, we utilize a combination of Gemini 2.0 Flash and Gemini 2.0 Pro.\"* — PAPER §2.3\n\n**A2.** The ensemble splits roles by cost/quality: **Flash maximizes breadth/throughput** (lower latency → more candidates), **Pro provides occasional higher-quality/breakthrough suggestions**. *\"Gemini 2.0 Flash, with its lower latency, enables a higher rate of candidate generation... Gemini 2.0 Pro... provides occasional, higher-quality suggestions that can significantly advance the evolutionary search and potentially lead to breakthroughs.\"* — PAPER §2.3 (BLOG: Flash \"maximizes the breadth of ideas explored\"; Pro \"provides critical depth\").\n\n**A3.** The pipeline has four components plus a controller: **Prompt sampler, LLMs ensemble, Evaluators pool, Program database**, driven by an asynchronous **Distributed Controller Loop**. — PAPER §2 / Figure 2\n\n**A4.** The loop, in DeepMind's words: *\"The Prompt sampler uses programs from the Program database to construct rich prompts... the LLMs generate code modifications (diffs), which are applied to create new programs... These are then scored by Evaluators, and promising solutions are registered back into the Program database.\"* — PAPER §2. Core pseudocode: `diff = llm.generate(prompt)`; `child_program = apply_diff(parent_program, diff)`; `results = evaluator.execute(child_program)`. — PAPER\n\n**A5.** Mutation is **diff-based by default** — LLMs emit `<<<<<<< SEARCH / ======= / >>>>>>> REPLACE` blocks for \"targeted updates to specific parts of the code\"; full rewrites are a configurable alternative for very short code. Evolvable regions are marked with `# EVOLVE-BLOCK-START / END`. — PAPER §2.1, §2.3\n\n**A6.** Candidates are scored by **executing a user-provided Python `evaluate` function `h`** returning a dictionary of scalar metrics (maximized). Supports an **evaluation cascade** (cheap→expensive test stages) and **multi-objective** scoring (which \"often improves results for the single target metric\"). — PAPER §2.1, §2.4\n\n**A7.** Selection/storage uses an evolutionary database combining **MAP-Elites + island-based population models**, \"balancing exploration and exploitation... while maintaining diversity.\" — PAPER §2.5\n\n**A8.** AlphaEvolve is **model-agnostic** and \"performs increasingly better as the underlying LLM improves.\" It is positioned as a successor to / generalization of **FunSearch** (which evolved a single short function; AlphaEvolve evolves entire files and can evaluate for hours in parallel on accelerators). — PAPER §1, §2.3\n\n---\n\n## 2. The verifier / evaluation function — a fundamental constraint\n\n**V1.** AlphaEvolve only tackles **machine-gradable** problems; the user MUST supply an automated assessor. *\"Since AlphaEvolve tackles problems with machine-gradeable solutions, the user must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing generated solutions.\"* — PAPER §2.1 (note DeepMind's spelling \"machine-gradeable\").\n\n**V2.** That assessor is a function **h mapping a solution → a set of scalar metrics, which are maximized** (\"typically implemented as a Python function, called evaluate, ... returning a dictionary of scalars\"). — PAPER §2.1\n\n**V3.** The entire evolutionary loop is driven by this score: it is *\"an evolutionary algorithm that gradually develops programs that improve the score on the automated evaluation metrics.\"* BLOG: *\"AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics. These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"* — PAPER §2.4 / BLOG\n\n**V4 (the load-bearing caveat).** DeepMind frames the metric as both advantage and limitation: *\"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope. Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"* — PAPER (intro, near Table 1)\n\n**V5 (excluded classes).** Problems excluded by construction: (a) tasks requiring **manual experimentation** (V4); (b) **natural sciences** where \"only some experiments can be simulated or automated\" (PAPER §6); (c) **non-numerical / non-algorithmic** problems — secondary framing: AlphaEvolve \"can only describe solutions as algorithms, making it a poor fit for problems that aren't numerical\" (TechCrunch: https://techcrunch.com/2025/05/14/deepmind-claims-its-newest-ai-tool-is-a-whiz-at-math-and-science-problems/).\n\n**V6 (the only escape hatch, explicitly not optimized).** An optional LLM-as-judge feedback mechanism exists for qualities hard to capture in `h` (e.g. simplicity), *\"but this is not a setting we have optimized for.\"* — PAPER §6. The core loop still requires the machine score.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concrete results\n\n### Algorithms & mathematics\n**R1 (headline).** AlphaEvolve multiplies two **4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications**, beating the rank-**49** from recursively applying **Strassen's 1969 algorithm** — *\"the first improvement, after 56 years, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\"* — PAPER abstract/§3.1, BLOG.\n*Falsification note:* AlphaTensor's earlier 47-mult 4×4 result was over GF(2) (mod-2), not a general tensor decomposition; AlphaEvolve's 48 is the first valid complex/real recursive improvement — hence \"56 years.\" (IEEE Spectrum: https://spectrum.ieee.org/deepmind-alphaevolve)\n\n**R2.** Across **54 matrix-multiplication tensor targets**, AlphaEvolve matched SOTA in **38**, surpassed it in **14**, fell behind in **2**. — PAPER Tables 2–3.\n\n**R3.** Applied to **\"over 50\" open problems** in analysis, geometry, combinatorics: **matched** best-known constructions on **~75%**, and **surpassed SOTA / found new provably better constructions on ~20%**. — PAPER §1, BLOG, IEEE Spectrum.\n\n**R4 (kissing number).** Improved the **11-dimensional kissing number lower bound from 592 to 593**. *\"For d=11, the best known lower bound was 592 and AlphaEvolve improved this to 593.\"* — PAPER §B.11, BLOG. (Upper bound remains 868.)\n\n**R5 (other math, all PAPER appendix).** Erdős minimum overlap C₅ upper bound 0.380927 → **0.380924** (§B.5); uncertainty constant C₄ → **0.3521**, later **0.3216** with a refined approach (§B.4); sum/difference-set constant C₆ lower bound to **1.1584** via a 54,265-element set (§B.6); plus hexagon packing, Heilbronn-triangle, and min/max-distance-ratio improvements (§§B.7–B.10).\n\n### Google infrastructure & hardware\n**R6 (Borg).** A scheduling heuristic for Borg, *\"now in production for over a year, continuously recovers, on average, 0.7% of Google's worldwide compute resources\"* (BLOG); PAPER §3.3.1: \"recovers on average 0.7% of Google's fleet-wide compute resources, which would otherwise be stranded.\" Chosen over deep-RL for interpretability/debuggability.\n\n**R7 (TPU circuit).** AlphaEvolve proposed a **Verilog rewrite removing unnecessary bits** in a key TPU matrix-multiplication arithmetic circuit, validated by TPU designers, \"integrated into an upcoming TPU\" — \"Gemini's first direct contribution to TPU arithmetic circuits.\" — BLOG, PAPER §3.3.3.\n*Caveat (often dropped):* PAPER notes the improvement \"was also independently caught by downstream synthesis tools,\" and **no percentage** is quantified.\n\n**R8 (Gemini training kernel).** Optimizing the **tiling heuristic for a matrix-multiplication Pallas kernel** gave an **average 23% kernel speedup** → **1% reduction in Gemini's overall training time**; deployed in production; cut kernel optimization time from months to days. — BLOG, PAPER §3.3.2.\n\n**R9 (FlashAttention).** By directly editing XLA-generated IR, the **FlashAttention kernel was sped up by 32%** (PAPER §3.3.4) / **\"up to 32.5%\"** (BLOG) — *minor cross-source discrepancy, both primary* — plus a separate **15%** speedup on input/output pre/post-processing (PAPER only).\n\n---\n\n## 4. What AlphaEvolve CANNOT do (DeepMind's own caveats)\n\n**L1 (the main stated limitation, verbatim).** *\"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"* — PAPER §6.\n\n**L2 (scope = describable-as-algorithm + auto-verifiable).** BLOG: *\"...it can be applied to any problem whose solution can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified.\"* The flip side: anything not so describable/verifiable is excluded (see V5).\n\n**L3 (does NOT modify its own LLM weights).** AlphaEvolve improved the **training infrastructure** (the matmul kernel tiling used to train Gemini), explicitly **not** the model's weights: *\"The kernel's correctness is maintained by construction because AlphaEvolve is optimizing the tiling strategy for this kernel rather than altering [the computation].\"* — PAPER §3.3.2. It is *\"a test-time compute agent that... significantly enhances the capability of the base LLM\"* — i.e. enhancement via search at inference, not weight changes. — PAPER §6.\n\n**L4 (self-improvement of the model is FUTURE WORK, slow).** *\"...a natural next step will be to consider distilling the AlphaEvolve-augmented performance of the base LLMs into the next generation of the base models.\"* And: *\"...the gains are moderate and the feedback loops for improving the next version of AlphaEvolve are on the order of months.\"* — PAPER §6. This is the strongest verbatim evidence against a \"fast recursive self-improvement / takeoff\" reading.\n\n**L5 (LLM-as-judge not optimized).** See V6: the system in practice depends on programmatic evaluators; the LLM-feedback path is \"not a setting we have optimized for.\" — PAPER §6.\n\n**L6 (no AGI / no autonomy claim).** DeepMind's primary materials make no AGI or recursive-self-improvement claim; AlphaEvolve relies on **human-defined problems and metrics** and \"cannot independently identify or define new challenges\" (secondary framing: unite.ai — https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/).\n\n---\n\n### Reliability notes\n- Every load-bearing claim (architecture, the verifier constraint, all headline numbers, all four limitations) is anchored in **DeepMind's own white paper and/or blog**, the two highest-credibility primary sources. Secondary sources (TechCrunch, IEEE Spectrum, VentureBeat, unite.ai) are used only for framing, never as the sole basis for a number.\n- Two flagged nuances to carry forward: **FlashAttention 32% vs 32.5%** (paper vs blog), and the **TPU circuit caveat** that the rewrite was also independently found by synthesis tools and carries no quantified %.\n- The **AlphaTensor (GF(2), 47) vs AlphaEvolve (complex, 48)** distinction is the single most common way the headline matrix-mult claim gets garbled — keep them separate."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19742,"cache_read_input_tokens":15247,"output_tokens":4760,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":19742},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":4760,"cache_read_input_tokens":15247,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19742,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":19742,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2CyC57qmzuyrCfJixC","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"104e7f36-8404-4457-a3df-38cd1f0b23b9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:37:40.597Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
